As you said in your question the array is sorted and you want to count the occurrences of a particular element if it is present. This is a digression about binary search with the little difference that you have to search for an element in one array and see if the adiacent elements on the left and on the right are equal to your element. You can use the [`Arrays#binarySearch`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/util/Arrays.html#binarySearch-int:A-int-) method like below:

~~~
public class Main {
    
    public static int binarySearchCount(int[] a, int key) {
        int index = Arrays.binarySearch(a, key);
        
        if (index &lt; 0) { return 0; }
        
        int count = 1;
        //look for the adiacent elements on the left
        for (int i = index - 1; i &gt;= 0 &amp;&amp; a[i] == key; --i) { ++count; }

        //look for the adiacent elements on the right
        for (int i = index + 1; i &lt; a.length &amp;&amp; a[i] == key; ++i) { ++count; }


        return count;
    }
     
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] a = {1, 1, 2, 2, 2, 2, 3};
        System.out.println(binarySearchCount(a, 2)); //&lt;-- it will print 4
        System.out.println(binarySearchCount(a, 0)); //&lt;-- it will print 0
    }
}
~~~

