Probably the easiest way to do this is with an [`EnumMap`][1], an implementation of [`Map`][2] optimized for enum objects. 

Use your enum object as the key, and an `Integer` for count as the value of the map: `Map&lt;Food, Integer&gt;`. 

    Map&lt;Food, Integer&gt; counts = new EnumMap&lt;&gt;(food.class);
    for (Food f : arr) {
      counts.merge(f, 1, Integer::sum);
    }

...and then you could look up the counts in the map:

    int numberOfApples = counts.getOrDefault(Food.apples, 0);


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/EnumMap.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Map.html

